fields.description:
If a user tries to create a security group that already exists, Eucalyptus reports back with a Java error, instead of a AWS error code and message:

{code}
# euca-create-group zenlb-test -d "Test Security Group for Zen Loadbalancer and Windows"
CreateSecurityGroupType: CreateSecurityGroup failed because: java.lang.RuntimeException: Failed to create group: zenlb-test for arn:aws:euare::345590850920:user/admin
Caused by: com.eucalyptus.cloud.util.MetadataException: Failed to create group: zenlb-test for arn:aws:euare::345590850920:user/admin
Caused by: javax.persistence.PersistenceException: Error during transaction: Failed to create group: zenlb-test for arn:aws:euare::345590850920:user/admin
Caused by: com.eucalyptus.cloud.util.DuplicateMetadataException: Failed to create group: zenlb-test for arn:aws:euare::345590850920:user/admin
{code}

When testing against AWS, the error code and message are as follows:

{code}
$ ec2-create-group neo4j-cluster -d "Neo4j HA Cluster"
Client.InvalidGroup.Duplicate: The security group 'neo4j-cluster' already exists
{code}

Ran euca-create-group against AWS to rule out Euca2ools issue.  Issue is definitely with response provided by CLC:

{code}
# euca-create-group -a XXXXXXXX -s XXXXXX --url https://us-east-1.ec2.amazonaws.com neo4j-cluster -d "Neo4j HA Cluster"
InvalidGroup.Duplicate: The security group 'neo4j-cluster' already exists
{code}

*Reference*

* http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/APIReference/api-error-codes.html
